  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Criminal organizations historically sought ways to conceal illegal income\n\n2. United States Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required banks to report significant cash transactions\n\n3. International Developments\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention - First international treaty addressing money laundering\n- Focused on drug trafficking proceeds\n- Encouraged international cooperation in financial crime prevention\n\n4. Key Legislation\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Criminalized money laundering in the US\n- Patriot Act (2001) - Expanded AML regulations after 9/11\n- Significantly enhanced financial institution reporting requirements\n\n5. Global Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created recommendations for national legal and regulatory AML systems\n\n6. Modern Developments\n- Increasing focus on cryptocurrency and digital transaction monitoring\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n- More sophisticated technological tracking mechanisms\n\nThis overview reflects the progressive legal approach to addressing financial crimes.",
